        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request continuum observations in band 6 and ask for a standard correlator setup. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Angular scale: We expect the target to be a galaxy at high redshift. Assuming z=11 then 1 arcsec = 4 kpc projected distance. Assuming a galaxy with 10 kpc diameter, we arrive at 2.5 arcsec diameter.

Angular resolution: Observations of GRB host galaxies at low z show that (long) GRBs seem to occur within 1 kpc of a star-forming region. For an angular resolution of 0.15 arcsec, we would resolve about 0.6 kpc, what is fine to check if the position of the NIR counterpart of the afterglow is close to a submm "hot spot" (if we detect the GRB host galaxy).    </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request a deep pointing in band 6 to search for the host galaxy of a gamma-ray burst which afterglow most likely was Lyman dropped out in the NIR bands. We have chosen band 6 as a best compromise between sensitivity and atmospheric transmission issues. Our target might be a starforming galaxy around z=11. Using Arp 220 as a template for the spectral energy distribution of this galaxy, we can estimate how deep we can go with ALMA. If we reach 8 microJy rms, we can go down to 1/20 of the flux of the local ultraluminous infrared galaxy Arp 220, corresponding to a sensitivity in star formation rate in the order of 5-10 solar masses per year.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
