    <prp:abstract>Present-day galaxies suggest that the early universe was undergoing an episode of intense star formation activity. But when did these starbursts begin? GRBs are the brightest light houses in the universe and as such they can act as unprecedented pathfinders into the high-redshift domain. Most GRBs are due to supernova explosions of young stars. As such wherever a (long) GRB is observed, there must be an underlying galaxy. Here, we propose a deep pointing into the r=1.7 arcsec small X-ray error circle of the optically dark burst 100205A, where follow-up observations strongly suggest that its optical/NIR afterglow was Lyman dropped out due to very high redshift.</prp:abstract>
